      "side": 1,
      "message": "In the scenario this change addresses (issue #1185), the validation failure is a property of the conversation content, not of the serving device: the malformed commit is part of the replicated, immutable history, so every member device serves the same invalid repository. Counting per device multiplies the retry budget by the number of devices while every attempt is doomed, prolonging exactly the storm (git channel + ICE/TLS + one FCM push every ~5s) this change stops. And gating \"unrecoverable\" on distinct clone sources never converges for the most common topology: a peer with a single device -- the storm would then run forever.\n\nThe tampered-copy scenario (one malicious member device serving an invalid history while others hold a valid one) is possible in principle, but its blast radius is deliberately bounded and recoverable: the counter is in-memory only (a daemon restart grants a fresh bounded round), the clone source is whichever member device connects first (so three consecutive losses of that race by all honest devices is the corner of a corner case), and EUNRECOVERABLE gives the client an actionable recovery (remove + ask for a new invitation). Note also that a malicious conversation member can already deny service in simpler ways.\n\nA per-source blacklist (skip devices that served invalid data; give up once every announcing device is blacklisted) could be a follow-up hardening, but it adds dynamic state and edge cases for marginal gain over the restart recovery path.",
      "parentUuid": "bc83582c_ef9e4f68",
      "revId": "291e740044b039acc150436723d4ec7d23dffe12",
      "serverId": "1e26b4c1-6b8c-47ff-9df7-501b633d3b5a"
